SIMPLE: dudder
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Dudder
<hw>Dud"der</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[In Suffolk, Eng.,
to shiver, shake, tremble; also written <ets>dodder</ets>.]</ety>
<def>To confuse or confound with noise.</def>
<rj><au>Jennings.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Dudder</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Dudder
<hw>Dud"der</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To shiver or tremble; to
dodder.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I <qex>dudder</qex> and shake like an aspen leaf.</q>
<rj><qau>Ford.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Dudder</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Dudder
<hw>Dud"der</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Duds</er>.]</ety> <def>A
peddler or hawker, especially of cheap and flashy goods pretended to be
smuggled; a duffer.</def> <mark>[Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Duddery</ent>⟦br⟧
